Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fowke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name  <i>Folk</i>,  <i>Fulk</i>,  <i>Fuke</i>.  Compare  Foxon  . For a variant form of the personal name  see  Foulkes  .  See also  Fudge  , which may sometimes be a variant form."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulch</i> or <i>Fuche</i>, usually a pet form of Old French <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fucher</i> (see   Fulcher  ). Voicing of ‘ch’ to soft ‘g’ gave rise to <i>Fudge</i>. The name may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Fowke was born about 1494, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Fowke, was 32 and his mother, Jane Streethay, was 31. He married Margaret ( Majorie) Wharwood after 1505, in England, United Kingdom. He died on 10 March 1544, in his hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1494–10 March 1544":"umbes 1494–10. märts 1544","1487–Male":"1487–Surnud","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1495–1528":"1495–1528","–Female":"Surnud","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1480–1530":"1480–1530","1530–1558":"1530–1558","1463–1494":"1463–1494","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1561":"1561","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1480":"1480","Aft 1505":"pärast 1505","1558":"1558","1544":"1544","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1487":"1487","1530":"1530","1463":"1463","1509":"1509","about 1486":"umbes 1486","10 March 1544":"10. märts 1544","1528":"1528","about 1494":"umbes 1494",",, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1494–10 March 1544":"noin 1494–10. maaliskuuta 1544","1487–Male":"1487–Kuollut","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1495–1528":"1495–1528","–Female":"Kuollut","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1480–1530":"1480–1530","1530–1558":"1530–1558","1463–1494":"1463–1494","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1561":"1561","1495":"1495","1494":"1494","1480":"1480","Aft 1505":"1505 jälkeen","1558":"1558","1544":"1544","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1487":"1487","1530":"1530","1463":"1463","1509":"1509","about 1486":"noin 1486","10 March 1544":"10. maaliskuuta 1544","1528":"1528","about 1494":"noin 1494",",, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1494–10 Ma